<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title></title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:right"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">RCH0005</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Wr</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">itten Evidence submitted by </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Children’s Services Development Group</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> and the</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Independent Children’s Homes Association</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> (CSDG and ICHA)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Sector urges </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">DfE</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> to take a strategic approach to care system </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">With the closure of the DfE consultations on regulatory reform of children’s homes, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">t</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">he Children’s Services Development Group and the Independent Children’s Homes Association have joined together to express our concern that</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> the Government’s changes to care regulations will do little to protect vulnerable children form harm or abuse. Without a wider strategic approach to the care system, the Department for Education is hindering the comprehensive changes needed and stands only to reinforce the silos that already exist in children’s services. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">We welcome the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">intention of the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">changes</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, but are concerned that the narrow focus will not be effective</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> in protecting children and young people</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">All children should have safe, effective care whether in fostering, kinship care or children’s homes, and whether placed in- or out-of-area. Many children at risk of abuse and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">exploitation will still be living with their birth families, as was the case in Rochdale, and these changes do little to safeguard them.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">There is more that providers can do, but they cannot effect change alone. More has to be asked of social work</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> colleagues</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, schools, health services and the police in order to achieve effective multi-agency working. Revising regulations without acting to ensure effective implementation and better strategic commissioning of placements will not truly make a difference in the lives of children in the care system. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">DfE</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> has recognised that too often children’s homes are used by local authorities as a ‘last resort’. 7,900 of the 67,000 looked-after children in England are cared for in residential homes,</span><a name="_ftnref1"></a><a href="#_ftn1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and we believe that residential </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">care can and should play a vital role as part of a range of provision for children with complex needs.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Many </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">young people</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> in residential homes will have had multiple placement breakdowns and often have the most complex needs.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> Statistics released in the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Children’s Homes Data Pack</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> show that nearly a third of children in children’s homes have had 6 or more placements.</span><a name="_ftnref2"></a><a href="#_ftn2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> This is a scandal, with poor commissioning denying children stable and secure placements that meet their needs. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The DfE’s own data contradicts recent misleading statements made by the Education Secretary.</span><a name="_ftnref3"></a><a href="#_ftn3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> The </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Data Pack</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> shows that 71% of children’s homes are rated good or outstanding, and there is no direct correlation between level of deprivation and location of children’s homes.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Where homes are inadequate or located in unsafe areas, this must be addressed and quickly, but the majority of children’s homes </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">provide young people with intensive and specialist therapeutic support that will enable them to live fulfilled adult lives</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Where local authorities lack provision, and so turn to out-of-area placements, we would encourage them to work in partnership with providers to develop high quality provision that meets children’s needs. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Recent parliamentary questions have revealed that the DfE decided against developing a care strategy.</span><a name="_ftnref4"></a><a href="#_ftn4">[4]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> Instead the department has chosen to implement piecemeal reforms – such as to the adoption system – that do not impact upon the majority of looked-after children. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">We</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> would urge the</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> DfE</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> to</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> rethink this decision and</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> take a strategic approach to reforming</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> the wider care system in order </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">to best meet the needs of vulnerable children, rather than making piecemeal changes in </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">isolation.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> Only by doing so will they safeguard vulnerable children and help to provide the high-quality care and support they deserve.  </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Children’s Services Development Group</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The Children’s Services Development Group is a policy coalition of leading independent providers of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">specialist services for looked after children and young people with complex needs. Its members</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">–</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> Acorn Care &amp; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Education, Hesley Group, National Fostering Agency, Options Group, Priory Education Services, SENAD Group, Witherslack Group and Young Foundations</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> –</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> provide services to vulnerable young people, delivering excellent outcomes and value for money across the UK.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><a name="_GoBack"></a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Independent Children’s Homes Association</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The ICHA has extensive membership across the non-statutory Residential Child Care sector providing policy, practice and advocacy.  It works with Government, Ofsted, ADCS and is represented on national contracting and commissioning groups. </span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; margin:0pt"><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">September 2013</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; margin:0pt"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div><hr style="width:33%; height:1px; text-align:left" /><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn1"></a